problem_description:
Global problem:
    This problem involves a collection of items, where each have a value and a weight. We have 6 different items given in the parameters.
    We have a infinite number of boxes with width BOX_WIDTH and height BOX_HEIGHT. All items need to be packed into minimal number of such boxes.
    The result and expected output is:
        - the assigment of each item into a box
        - the position (x and y) of each item within its assigned box. x and y have minimum values 0 and maximum infinity.

Sub problem definition - items that go in the bin - part 1:
    The items that are put into a box, must fit exactly inside the box and must not stick out of the box.
    The result and expected output is the assigment of each item into a box and the position of each item within its assigned box.

Sub problem definition - items that go in the bin - part 2:
    Taking the given items that are put into a box, they must not overlap.
    The result and expected output is the assigment of each item into a box and the position of each item within its assigned box.

Sub problem definition - items that go in the bin - part 3:
    Taking the given items that are put into a box, one item can be exactly in one box.
    The result and expected output is the assigment of each item into a box and the position of each item within its assigned box.

constants.description: List of items with their dimensions

decision_variables.description: Number of boxes used to pack all items, minimized as objective
Assignment of each item to a box with position details
X and Y positions of each item within its assigned box

def items_fit_exactly_in_boxes(
    items: DSList(length=60, elem_type=Item),
    placements: DSList(length=60, elem_type=ItemPlacement),
    box_width: int,
    box_height: int
):
    for i in range(1, N_ITEMS + 1):
        # Ensure item placement respects box boundaries
        assert placements[i].x + items[i].width <= box_width
        assert placements[i].y + items[i].height <= box_height
        # Ensure item stays within positive coordinate bounds
        assert placements[i].x >= 0
        assert placements[i].y >= 0

items_fit_exactly_in_boxes(ITEMS, item_box_assignments, BOX_WIDTH, BOX_HEIGHT)

# --- constraints ---
def no_overlap_in_boxes(
    placements: DSList(length=60, elem_type=ItemPlacement),
    items: DSList(length=60, elem_type=Item)
):
    for i in range(1, N_ITEMS + 1):
        for j in range(i + 1, N_ITEMS + 1):
            # Only check overlap if both items are in the same box
            if placements[i].box_id == placements[j].box_id:
                # Assert that at least one axis does not overlap (i.e., items do not overlap)
                assert (placements[i].x + items[i].width <= placements[j].x) or \
                       (placements[j].x + items[j].width <= placements[i].x) or \
                       (placements[i].y + items[i].height <= placements[j].y) or \
                       (placements[j].y + items[j].height <= placements[i].y)

no_overlap_in_boxes(item_box_assignments, ITEMS)

# --- Auxiliary Variables ---
# Leave empty, if not required.
# --- constraints ---
def ensure_item_box_assignment_validity(
    placements: DSList(length=60, elem_type=ItemPlacement),
    nr_used_boxes: DSInt(lb=1, ub=65)
):
    for i in range(1, N_ITEMS + 1):
        # Ensure each item is assigned to a box within the valid range
        assert placements[i].box_id >= 1
        assert placements[i].box_id <= nr_used_boxes

ensure_item_box_assignment_validity(item_box_assignments, nr_used_boxes)

# --- constraints ---
def no_overlap(
    assignments: DSList(length=60, elem_type=BoxAssignment),
    items: DSList(length=60, elem_type=Item)
):
    for i in range(1, N_ITEMS + 1):
        for j in range(i + 1, N_ITEMS + 1):
            # Only check items assigned to the same box
            if assignments[i].box_id == assignments[j].box_id:
                # No overlap condition: one of the following must hold
                # i is to the right of j
                # i is to the left of j
                # i is above j
                # i is below j
                assert (assignments[i].x >= assignments[j].x + items[j].width) or \
                       (assignments[j].x >= assignments[i].x + items[i].width) or \
                       (assignments[i].y >= assignments[j].y + items[j].height) or \
                       (assignments[j].y >= assignments[i].y + items[i].height)

        assert assignments[i].y + items[i].height <= BOX_HEIGHT

problem_description:
Global problem:
    This problem involves a collection of items, where each have a value and a weight. We have 6 different items given in the parameters.
    We have a infinite number of boxes with width BOX_WIDTH and height BOX_HEIGHT. All items need to be packed into minimal number of such boxes.
    The result and expected output is:
        - the assigment of each item into a box
        - the position (x and y) of each item within its assigned box. x and y have minimum values 0 and maximum infinity.

Sub problem definition - items that go in the bin - part 1:
    The items that are put into a box, must fit exactly inside the box and must not stick out of the box.
    The result and expected output is the assigment of each item into a box and the position of each item within its assigned box.

Sub problem definition - items that go in the bin - part 2:
    Taking the given items that are put into a box, they must not overlap.
    The result and expected output is the assigment of each item into a box and the position of each item within its assigned box.

Sub problem definition - items that go in the bin - part 3:
    Taking the given items that are put into a box, one item can be exactly in one box.
    The result and expected output is the assigment of each item into a box and the position of each item within its assigned box.

decision_variables.description: Number of boxes used to pack all items, minimized in the objective
